Setup — your first SparkSession.

To run the notebook locally, you need java seventeen or higher installed. Then pip install pyspark version three point five point three.

The pattern is the same every time. Build a SparkSession builder, give it an app name, point it at local mode, and call get-or-create. The returned object is your handle to everything Spark — reading data, registering views, running queries.

One key note on get-or-create. It is sticky. If a SparkSession already exists in your kernel — from a previous cell, a previous notebook, or anywhere else — the builder returns that existing session and silently ignores any new configuration you set on the new builder. To pick up new config in a running notebook, you have to call spark dot stop first, then build again.
